06620nam a22010095i 9783110695113DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020935871  a97831106951137 a10.1515/97831106951132doi  a(DE-B1597)545959  a(OCoLC)1198929311  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE04aThe Learnability of Complex Constructions :bA Cross-Linguistic Perspective /ced. by Marcel Schlechtweg. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (V, 240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ;v34500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tLexical co-activation with prefixed cognates and non-cognates: Evidence from cross-script masked priming -- tDifferences in acoustic detail: The realization of syncretic nouns in German -- tDoes the processing of first language compounds change in late bilinguals? -- tPlanning complex structures in a second language: Compounds and phrases in non-native speech production -- tThe learnability of English intensifying constructions in French-speaking learners: Receptive versus productive competence -- tIs it hard to learn multiple word orders? -- tThe learnability of gender agreement in Spanish bilinguals -- tAgreement mismatches in the Spanish preterite of Catalan-dominant bilinguals in Majorca: A receding interlanguage phenomenon -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow language users from different linguistic backgrounds cope with forms of complexity is still a territory with many unanswered questions. The current book is concerned with morphologically and syntactically complex items, that is, derivatives, inflected forms, compounds, phrases and forms related by agreement and examines how these constructions are acquired and learned in a great range of different languages, such as Turkish, Welsh, Basque and Catalan. Relying on a variety of methodologies targeting production or comprehension, among others, lexical decision and priming experiments, an EEG study, a corpus analysis and a reading test, the authors consider data from native speakers mastering one or more languages and second-language users. Overall, the volume reflects upon and contributes to our understanding of how the pecularities of language and its users affect the learnability of complex forms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 4aErstspracherwerb. 4aLernfähigkeit. 4aZweitspracherwerb. 4akomplexe Konstruktionen.  aComplex constructions.  aLanguage Acquisition.1 aCaffarra, Sendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCostello, Brendan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDias, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnrique-Arias, Andrés, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGürel, Ayşe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeinrichs, Melina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendrikx, Isa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLahiri, Aditi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinnenkohl, Marcel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNicoladis, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchlechtweg, Marcel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchlechtweg, Marcel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aUygun, Serkan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVoga, Madeleine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.